<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[491,1541,228,1914]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[491,619,346,372]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[628,872,347,373]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Meranoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mosalahi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[628,872,347,373]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Meranoplus mosalahi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[882,947,347,373]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be diagnosed by the following characters: Anterior clypeal margin shallowly concave or straight with one pair of reduced tubercles; clypeal surface smooth, or with two pairs of indistinct longitudinal rugae; the eye merely abuts the scrobal cavity and, in full-face view, the scrobe is narrowly visible; cephalic surface to posterior level of eyes with irregular interrupted longitudinal rugae (about 12 rugae); ground surface between rugae finely punctate; anterior face of petiolar node smooth; posterior face feebly sculptured with about five longitudinal rugae; bicolored species with head, and gaster brown, antennae, mesosoma, petiole and postpetiole light brown, legs yellow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
